        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Tucson, AZ: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Tucson, AZ, your fire extinguishers are a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Tucson Fire Department. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and the Arizona Fire Code (IFC-based) require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Tucson Fire Extinguisher Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Tucson enforces the Arizona Fire Code (IFC-based), requiring all commercial properties to maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers</a>. Tucson's commercial landscape includes the 4th Avenue and Congress Street entertainment and dining districts, the University of Arizona campus commercial zone, significant Davis-Monthan Air Force Base support operations, and growing biotechnology and research facilities in the Tucson Innovation District. Tucson's desert climate — summer temperatures regularly exceeding 100°F — accelerates dry chemical agent degradation in extinguishers, particularly in outdoor and poorly ventilated storage locations.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly visual inspections can be performed by trained building staff — no license required. Verify each extinguisher is in its designated location, unobstructed, the pressure gauge reads in the operating range, and the tamper seal and pull pin are intact. Document every check. Absence of monthly records significantly increases liability exposure in the event of an incident or enforcement action.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Annual inspections must be performed by a licensed technician who inspects mechanical parts, agent condition, pressure gauge, hose and nozzle, and attaches a dated service tag. Arizona requires fire extinguisher service contractors to hold appropriate credentials under Arizona state law, overseen by the Arizona State Fire Marshal's Office (602-364-1003). Verify your service provider holds current Arizona credentials before scheduling service. Any failed unit must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure extinguishers must be emptied, disassembled, and internally examined for corrosion and agent degradation. This typically includes a full recharge after examination. Missing the 6-year exam is frequently cited during Tucson Fire Department commercial property inspections.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At 12 years, extinguisher cylinders must pass hydrostatic pressure testing to verify structural integrity. Units that fail must be condemned and cannot be returned to service. Budget for some units to require replacement at this interval.</p>
